PART 1 : PROJECT OVERVIEW
Project Title
Sensor‑Based Behavioural Biometric Fraud Detection for Mobile Payment Interfaces

Main Objective
Develop a system that uses gyroscope and accelerometer data collected during mobile payment sessions (PhonePe‑like interface) to automatically authenticate the legitimate user and detect fraudulent transactions.
The core goal is to improve authentication accuracy from a baseline of ~69 % to ≥90 %, while keeping the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) below 0.5 % and the False Rejection Rate (FRR) within reasonable limits.

Problem Statement
Mobile payment apps are vulnerable to fraud. Traditional PIN‑based or password‑based authentication can be compromised. Behavioural biometrics – using how a user interacts with the device (touch, motion, navigation) – offers an additional layer of security.

However, the raw sensor data is high‑dimensional (~441 hand‑crafted features) and the One‑Class SVM (OCSVM) model used is sensitive to noise, feature redundancy, and hyperparameters. The project must:

Determine which of the many engineered features truly discriminate genuine users from impostors.

Optimise the OCSVM hyperparameters (nu, gamma, threshold) per user.

Build a pipeline that can be extended to new users while maintaining high accuracy and low error rates.

Final Expected Output
A production‑ready feature‑selection pipeline (Phases 1‑5) that, given raw CSV files, outputs a final list of the most discriminative features.

A tuned per‑user OCSVM model with fixed hyperparameters that can authenticate sessions in real time.

A rigorous validation framework (Leave‑One‑User‑Out) that provides honest, unbiased performance estimates.

A handoff document enabling any future team to reproduce and extend the work.

