Important Terminology
Session: One complete interaction with the payment app, from app launch to completion (or a defined timeframe). Contains sensor events, touch events, navigation events.

OCSVM (One‑Class SVM): A support vector machine that learns a boundary around a single class (genuine samples). Any sample falling outside the boundary is considered an outlier (fraud).

RBF kernel: Radial Basis Function kernel used in OCSVM; it maps data into a higher‑dimensional space to find a non‑linear boundary.

nu: Upper bound on the fraction of training errors and lower bound on the fraction of support vectors. Controls the tightness of the boundary.

gamma: Kernel coefficient for RBF. Determines the influence of a single training sample. Larger gamma → more complex boundary.

threshold: Decision score above which a sample is classified as genuine. Usually 0, but can be tuned.

FRR (False Rejection Rate): Proportion of genuine sessions incorrectly classified as fraud.

FAR (False Acceptance Rate): Proportion of impostor sessions incorrectly classified as genuine.

TAR (True Acceptance Rate): 1 – FRR.

HTER (Half Total Error Rate): (FRR + FAR) / 2.

LOUO (Leave‑One‑User‑Out): A cross‑validation strategy where each user is used once as the test set while all other users form the training set.

Boruta: A wrapper feature‑selection algorithm that uses random forest to identify all relevant features.

SHAP: SHapley Additive exPlanations – a game‑theoretic method to explain the output of machine learning models; used here to rank features after Boruta.

Fisher Score: Ratio of between‑class variance to within‑class variance. Measures how well a feature separates different users.

RF LOUO Importance: Feature importance derived from a Random Forest trained on other users’ genuine vs. impostor data.

Consensus ranking: Aggregation of multiple feature rankings (weighted average of percentiles).

drop_cols: A list in the training script that defines which features are excluded from the model.

HMOG: Hand Movement, Orientation, and Grasp – a set of behavioural features extracted during touch events.

MFCC: Mel‑Frequency Cepstral Coefficients – a representation of the short‑term power spectrum, commonly used in audio but adapted for motion signals.

Multitaper: A spectral estimation method that uses multiple orthogonal tapers to reduce variance.

